About The Data¶

The dataset has been taken from Kaggle.

Our Natural Images dataset contains 6,899 images from 8 different classes inclduing: airplane, car, cat, dog, flower, fruit, motorbike and person.

  • Airplane: 727 images
  • Car: 968 images
  • Cat: 885 images
  • Dog: 702 images
  • Flower: 843 images
  • Fruit: 1000 images
  • Motorbike: 788 images
  • Person: 986 images

For obtaining training and validation images from each class, we split the classes into two parts 80:20 for training and validation respectively. This resulted in a total of 5522 images obtained for our training set and 1377 images for our validation set.

In [28]:
#Model 2 Dropout after flattening and before softmax 
num_classes = 8
# do a batch norm where we have dropout (before max pool after conv)
model = tf.keras.Sequential([
  layers.experimental.preprocessing.Rescaling(1./255),
  layers.Conv2D(16, 3, activation='relu'),
  layers.MaxPooling2D(),
  layers.Conv2D(16, 3, activation='relu'),
  layers.MaxPooling2D(),
  layers.Conv2D(16, 3, activation='relu'),
  layers.MaxPooling2D(),
  layers.Flatten(),
  # add dropout layer
  layers.Dropout(rate=0.05),
  layers.Dense(32, activation='relu'),
  # another dropout 
  layers.Dropout(rate=0.05),
  layers.Dense(num_classes, activation = 'softmax')
])

Compile Model¶

In [29]:
model.compile(
  optimizer= tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(0.001),
  loss=tf.losses.SparseCategoricalCrossentropy(from_logits=True),
  metrics=['accuracy'])

Quantitative Analysis¶

Model 1 Visuals

As shown in the consusin matrix above for model 1, both airplanes and cars were misclassified as being flowers one time each within our 32 image batch. Due to this producing a 0.00% precision, accuracy, and f1-scores for those respective classes, we will be looking at the weighted the averages eliminate the impact of these "outliers". Model 2 produced a 4% higher level of precision, 3% greater recall, and 4% higher f1-score across the weighted averages. Also, our second model miscalssified a dog as a cat which is a reasonable mistake compared to airplanes and flowers in model 1. Overall model 2 outperformed model 1 which is why we used that infrastructure in our final run.

Accuracy = TP+TN/TP+FP+FN+TN

Precision = TP/TP+FP

Recall = TP/TP+FN

The curve above shows an abrupt change in slope on the loss curve compared to the second model which was much smoother due to our placement and degree of dropout which also aided in preventing overfitting.
